<h1>Engagement</h1>
<p>Engagement has emerged as an alternative view of the learner experience that can enrich the often
    reductionist language of performance, skills and competence. That is to say that the more one values
    the latter measures the more important it becomes to understand learner engagement.  For
    <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/03075070020030689">Mann (2001)</a> it becomes useful to reframe how
    we view the student's experience of learning, from a focus on surface/strategic/deep approaches to
    learning to a focus on alienated or engaged experiences of learning. When engaged a student may
    demonstrate a variety of strategies and approaches and is likely to achieve greater success.</p>

<p>Understanding engagement is complex and Infinite Rooms adopts
    <a href="http://www.adobe.com/engagement/">Haven's (2007)</a> process of engagement (below) to further
    explore and develop an understanding of what we can know via learner participation (or lack thereof).
    In this approach, for example,
    <a href="http://www.ifets.info/index.php?http://www.ifets.info/issues.php?id=56">MacFadyen and Dawson (2012)</a>
    suggest that common activities such as checking announcements, viewing grades and uploading assignments
    represent little time investment from the user and may not be useful indicators of engagement.</p>
