<p class="well well-small"><strong>Involvement </strong>describes the presence of a learner and
    includes data such as physical or virtual visits. While this is not a key indicator in itself these
    activities are critical to make connections with the other components and metrics.</p>
<p class="well well-small"><strong>Interaction</strong> provides a depth of understanding that
    involvement does not: where involvement measures touches, interaction measures actions. In the
    context of learning, development is more dependent on meaningful experience of activity than the
    particulars of performance.</p>
<p class="well well-small"><strong>Intimacy</strong> goes beyond interaction to help understand
    sentiment and affection. The most common way to collect this type of data is through interviews
    or surveys and sentiment analysis. One may look to Dweck’s self-theory, Deci and Ryan’s
    self-determination theory, and Pintrich’s Motivated Strategies for Learning Questionnaire (MSLQ)
    as validated approaches to understanding attitudes to learning.</p>
<p class="well well-small"><strong>Influence</strong> extends beyond sentiment to determine the
    likelihood of the individual sharing their learning with others. One may explore network analysis
    and link throughs to determine contributions to local culture through action as determined by
    theories like Harré’s participation pathway.</p>
